<TITLE> Chinese army buglers blow own trumpets at wargames </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Sept 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Buglers with China's People's Liberation Army are still sounding forth their trumpets, after war game exercises showed more sophisticated communications systems could be jammed, the Xinhua news agency said on Wednesday. After nearly being sifted out as the PLA adopted modern technology, buglers were jubilant to be included in the seven-day Queshan 2007 military exercise that began on Sept. 22, Xinhua said. The exercises showcase advanced technology, but also anticipate its failure. In the exercise, PLA buglers deliver combat orders after their units' radio signals are jammed by a strong electrical disturbance -- a problem first identified in war games in 2004. "Being a bugler was not a promising career in the past," sergeant Zhang Gaosen, a bugler with the Jinan Military Area Command, told Xinhua. Zhang has trained to sound his bugle in different positions, including on his back or on the run, Xinhua said. Buglers are also charged with mastering other basic communications tools, including hand gestures, lights, signals, sounds and smoke, Xinhua not
